A new wave looks to be underway in numerous provinces, driven by variants. Vaccination rates are simply too low/slow right now to combat this, and may not be fully effective against the variants anyway. Lockdown measures are increasing, but will have a lagging effect on new cases.

New reactive restrictions being imposed across Ontario [1] signal the delayed realisation of the third wave that was arguably inevitable with the relaxation of measures and the slow pace of the vaccination programme. That said the last 48 hours on here are testament to how so many were caught out with the exponential rise in cases in the relatively short period (including me!) and how impactful the UK COVID variant (B.1.1.7) [2] can be on case rates in more relaxed transmission environments.
Third wave. Renewed restrictions and vaccines will help but both are too little too late. Late April/early May border if people follow the new rules. April if they don’t.

With these margin call predictions it may be worth mentioning, for anyone using the more accessible and visually pleasant “our world indata” website [1] that the PHAC website against which this question will be decided [2] consistently lags about 5000 to 6000 cases per day behind it in total figures. This means that the Question will probably resolve a day or so after the world in data site records crossing the 1.1 mil threshold (for anyone tracking a prediction that falls on the 29th or 30th April 21 boundary!).

Currently, about 4.3k cases/day. If cases stayed absolutely flat at this level, there would be 146.2k more cases by April 30. 965k + 146.2k = 1.11M. I don't see any way that cases will maintain an average as low as 4.3k through April, as B.1.1.7 becomes dominant and control policies are not implemented. I expect the number of cases/day to continue to grow through April, with at most some slowing in the rate of growth due to weather or changes in individual behavior.

Active cases (30.6k) and the spread of variants of concern (2,728 B.1.1.7 in total) are on the rise, and Ontario seems to become the epicenter of all trouble: All three VoC currently under scrutiny are now domiciled in Ontario in significant numbers. 956 B.1.1.7; 41 B.1.351; 28 P.1 Reports from Germany are worrying that there are cases with a variant on record that are by and large cross-variants of B.1.1.7&B.1.351. If those combinations occur in CA, too, the real trouble likely begins. Canada is 200k cases and 50 days from the most interesting bin threshold away, so 4k new cases a day for the next seven weeks on average is the standard to watch.

New cases have started to stabilize after declining from peak of second wave. Unfortunately they are stabilizing above 2500 cases per day. If that holds it is still possible to have more than 1.1 M cases by 30 April with a small uptick in daily new cases.

The good news is: the virus seems to be under control in Alberta, British Columbia, which means suppression of the B.1.1.7 variant there at the same time. The bad news: Ontario's numbers tend to surge, 1,185 as of 09 March 2021 (which is ~40% of Canada's daily total), active cases are still higher than 30k, B.1.1.7 is still gaining (2,480 cases know from Dec 2020) in incidence, and Ontario is host to that variant predominantly (908 known cases, 37% of the total)

Active cases have not dropped below 30,000 for a number of days now, which indicates that revealing infections through testing does not keep pace with new infection chains at the moment.

Some math based on 22 Jan totals (706,495 cases). The peak daily case load was around 8,000 in late Dec-early Jan, most likely exacerbated by holiday travel and get-togethers and winter weather keeping people meeting indoors. Since then, cases have decreased significantly back near the 2,000 per day level. Even if there is another wave, it is doubtful cases would go near the previous peak of 8,000. Assuming an average of 4,000 cases per day, it would take 98 days to get above 1.1 million - a date of late April. Numerous factors could tend or shorten this timeline. Things like mitigation policies, vaccination administration, and even weather can affect the case load growth rates.
Even with my own judgement on possible errors and avenues down the road, I still come up with a relatively high confidence sometime in May, Canada will record 1.1 million total cases of COVID.

This is clearly following the flu season trend. In order to break 1.1 mil before 1 June Canada has to gain an average of 2858 cases a day. They are now at about 4k a day and dropping. Looking at the normal flu season arc it will drop below 2858/day in a month or less.

I'm afraid the recent slowing in figures gives a false sense of security. Canada certainly is on a "reduce"-scenario path and in a similar position as in mid-December 2020. However, like elsewhere there's a large risk for raging infection waves in long-term care facilities, the 80+ years group thus are the group with the highest incidence in the population. It seems Canada was able to avoid the worst scenarios and expectations for the time being, but there is plenty of examples where it can go the wrong way pretty quickly (e.g. Rep. Ireland). The next "Update on COVID-19 in Canada: Epidemiology and Modelling" is likely due to be published on 29 January 2021.

According to https://health-infobase.canada.ca/covid-19/epidemiological-summary-covid-19-cases.html?stat=num&measure=total_last7&map=pt#a2 there were 4,852 new confirmed cases on 24 January 2021. There is apparently a sharp drop in all provinces except from New Brunswick and Saskatchewan and a drop in particular in those provinces with the largest base of total reported cases so far (the main drivers of the pandemic in Canada), namely Alberta, Ontario and Quebec. However, it appears premature to pick a later bin than March for several reasons, the most prominent of which is an earlier observation in the source PHAC's figures: The daily differential of total cases for Canada often times exceeds the figure of daily new confirmed cases significantly (3 to 4 digits) without explanation. Consulting the daily new confirmed cases only could deliver a false impression of the trajectory of the real infection rate, caused by mismatching figures and revisions that are not announced. PHAC's figures are notoriously incomplete and unreliable. I expect Canada to count 150,000 additional cases to cross 900k cases in total over the next three weeks by 17 February 2021 (daily average 7.2k cases), which would leave six more weeks for the remaining 200,000 new cases (average of 4.8k cases per day) to reach 1.1mn cases. If 900k cases will not be reached by the end of February, then April is the most likely outcome of this question.
